        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="head" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Vlisses.</marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Odysseus"/>
                </position>
            </language>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian" anchor_text="Ulisses knew the time &amp; place, where hardinesse might preuayle.">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="left_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Vbi, et Quando, duo preciosissima pra[e]dicamenta.</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Where and when, two most precious predicated events.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="left_margin" book_orientation="270">
                    <marginalia_text>Ex abundantia cordis, os loquit[u]r; manus, pedesq[ue] operant[u]r. Nescia virtus stare loco.</marginalia_text>
                    <X-ref person="Luke" book_title="Gospel of Luke" language="LA" text="Ex abundantia cordis, os loquitur"/>
                    <X-ref person="Lucan" book_title="Pharsalia" text="Nescia virtus stare loco."/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>"From the abundance of the heart, the mouth speaks." The hand and feet work. "Virtue does not know how to rest."</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="right_margin" book_orientation="270">
                    <marginalia_text>Est Deus in nobis: agitante calescimus illo. Languent homines, suoru[m] animorum impotes.</marginalia_text>
                    <X-ref person="Ovid" book_title="Ars amatoria" language="LA" text="Est Deus in nobis: agitante calescimus illo"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>"God is in us, by whose movement we are inflamed." Men are tired, not in control of their soul.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Vis consilij expers, mole ruit sua. Leo sine vulpe insolescit: vulpes sine leone vilescit. Nusq[ua]m Ciphra.</marginalia_text> <!--JG: Seems to me that Harvey quoted 'leo...vilescit' as well. Can't find it, though-->
                    <!--KS: Could it be in reference to Aesop's fable of the lion and the fox? Can't find an exact quote, however.-->
                    <!-- JG: Possible, that's an interesting suggestion. Can't find an exact quote either, though: http://www.mythfolklore.net/aesopica/osius/44.htm-->
                    <X-ref person="Horace" book_title="Odes" language="LA" text="Vis consilij expers, mole ruit sua"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>"Force without wisdom falls of its own weight." The Lion becomes haughty without the fox; the fox becomes worthless without the lion. Nowhere a cipher.</translation> <!--JG: Last part is somewhat perplexing?-->
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="English_secretary">
            <language ident="EN">
                <position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>( Traynes, wyles.</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
        </marginalia>
            
